# Copy to .env and set strong values (or run `make up`, which generates all three).
#
# The Django SECRET_KEY is deliberately NOT set here. The container generates it and
# persists it at first boot (docs/security/threat-model.md, TM-8). There are no default
# credentials anywhere: compose refuses to start until all three passwords are set.
#
# Three database roles (ADR-004 role split, threat model TS-PG-1):
#   POSTGRES_PASSWORD          the bootstrap superuser; initdb, healthchecks, backups only
#   POSTGRES_MIGRATOR_PASSWORD backyard_migrator; owns the schema, runs migrations
#   POSTGRES_APP_PASSWORD      backyard_app; what the application runs as (no DDL)

POSTGRES_PASSWORD=
POSTGRES_MIGRATOR_PASSWORD=
POSTGRES_APP_PASSWORD=

# Optional overrides (defaults shown):
# DJANGO_DEBUG=0
# DJANGO_ALLOWED_HOSTS=localhost,127.0.0.1
# BACKYARD_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8000
# POSTGRES_DB=backyard
# POSTGRES_USER=backyard
